Part I - (Prosper Loan Data Exploration)¶

by (Utibe Edet Bassey)¶

Introduction¶

In this "Communicate Data Findings" project, I will be analyzing the Prosper loan dataset to determine the relationship between its features. Univariate plots will be plotted to discover the distribution of selected features after which bivariate plots will be made to uncover the effect of one feature on the other and lastly multivariate plots will be plotted based on the trends discovered in the previous plots to find out if addition of more features strengthens the relationsips found.

Dataset description: The Prosper loan dataset contains information from over 113,000 loans from Prosper marketplace which is a peer-to-peer lending marketplace in the United States founded in 2005. The dataset consists of 113937 rows with 81 variables (columns) on each loan, including loan original amount, borrower rate, current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Questions for analysis¶

  1. What are the distributions of some of the variables of interest?
  2. How did borrowers without prosper rating fare in the status of the their loan?
  3. Does prosper rating after Borrower's Annual percentage rate?
  4. Is BorrowerAPR the reason for the distribution observed in years 2013 and 2014?
  5. Does income range influence borrowerAPR?
  6. What is the relationship between BorrowerAPR and DebtToIncomeRatio?
  7. What was the borrowerAPR of borrowers without prosper rating?
  8. What was the borrowerAPR of borrowers without prosper rating?
  9. What kind of Terms were given to borrowers based on their Prosper rating?
  10. Does Debt-to-income ratio have an effect on borrowers' loan status?
  11. What is the relationship between ProsperRating_Combined and DebtToIncomeRatio?
  12. Do more investors go to high income earners?
  13. What was the reason for the distribution observed in years 2013 and 2014?
  14. Does being a group member influence BorrowerAPR for borrowers without ProsperRating_Combined value?
  15. What is the effect of Term on BorrowerAPR and ProsperRating_Combined?
  16. What is the relationship of Borrower Annual Percentage Rate across ProsperRating_Combined and IncomeRange?
  17. What is the effect of Income range across DebtToIncomeRatio and ProsperRating_Combined?

According to the Documentation in www.prosper.com/Downloads/Services/Documentation/ProsperAPI_Objects_Details.html CreditGrade and ProsperRating's values are CreditGrade 0(NC), 1(HR), 2(E), 3(D), 4(C), 5(B), 6(A), 7(AA) and ProsperRating 0(NA), 1(HR), 2(E), 3(D), 4(C), 5(B), 6(A), 7(AA). So I will create a new column to combine CreditGrade and ProsperRating_Alpha into one column (ProsperRating_Combined).

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,9937 loans in this dataset with 81 features which include 'ListingKey', 'ListingNumber', 'ListingCreationDate', 'CreditGrade', 'Term', 'LoanStatus', 'ClosedDate', 'BorrowerAPR', 'BorrowerRate', and 'LenderYield'. Due to the large number of features(81), I have selected a few to work with which I named 'columnsOfInterest' and created a new dataframe (prosper_df) based on those columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in discovering what features influence the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (BorrowerAPR) in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that ProsperRating_Combined (combination of CreditGrade and ProsperRating_Alpha) should have the strongest effect on prosper_df's borrowerAPR: the higher the ProsperRating_Combined, the lower the borrowerAPR. I also think that IncomeRange, IncomeVerifiable, Recommendations, Occupation, ListingCategory_numeric (the reason for the loan), EmploymentStatus, Term, IsBorrowerHomeowner, DebtToIncomeRatio, CurrentlyInGroup, and PublicRecordsLast10Years will have effects on the borrowerAPR too.

def percentage(variable): 
    total= 113937
    #find the percentage and round it to 1 decimal place
    percent= round(((variable/total)*100), 1) 
    percent_age = str(percent) + '%'  # convert to string and append the percentage symbol %
    print(percent_age)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The BorrowerAPR variable contained null values so I had to drop the nulls to be able to plot a histogram of the variable. The distribution showed that the BorrowerAPR is multimodal with its highest peak between 0.35 and 0.4.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I had already tidied CreditGrade and ProsperRating_Alpha columns to form the ProsperRating_Combined column because using either of them will not properly depict the information as only CreditGrade has ratings for pre-2009 and ProsperRating_Alpha has ratings for post-2009. Merging them allowed me see the distribution of Prosper's rating at a glance. I extracted the Year column after changing the datatype of ListingCreationDate column from a string to timestamp to explore the distribution of Year. I also selected borrowers without a prosper rating to see how they fared in their loan status.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The expected relationship of a negative corrrelation between ProsperRating_Combined and BorrowerAPR was observed as the higher the ProsperRating_Combined (excluding the NC rate that was discontinued after 2009) the lower the BorrowerAPR. Income range also showed a negative correlation with BorrowerAPR as the income increased from Very_low to High, the BorrowerAPR reduced though the negative correlation did not exist for borrowers without ProsperRating_Combined values. There was no correlation between DebtToIncomeRatio with BorrowerAPR which shows that BorrowerAPR was not directly dependent on DebtToIncomeRatio.

The consistent increase in year from 2009 to 2013 and the sudden decrease in year 2014 in the univariate plot for Year was explored to determine if BorrowerAPR influenced it. In the bivariate plot of Year against BorrowerAPR there was a decrease in BorrowerAPR only from 2012 to 2014 so lower BorrowerAPR was not the main reason for the increase in loans gotten from year 2009 to 2013 nor was it the reason for the drop in 2014 since lower borrowerAPR should have increased the number of loans as in the case of 2013. Further exploration would be carried out on this.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

There was a weak negative correlation between ProsperRating_Combined and DebtToIncomeRatio. There was a consistent increase in the number of investors from Very_low to High income range.

Conclusion¶

I selected BorrowerAPR as my main feature of interest after I had studied the Prosper loan dataset and selected some features to work with as I could not use the whole 81 columns. Selected features like BorrowerAPR, ProsperRating_Combined, IncomeRange, Year, and Term were plotted to visualize their distributions and examine trends. After the univariate plots of the selected columns, I paired them to find the effect of one variable on the other for the bivariate section. Plotting BorrowerAPR against ProsperRating_Combined showed a negative correlation excluding the No Credit rating which was discontinued after July 2009. BorrowerAPR against IncomeRange also showed a negative correlation for income range from Very_low (\$1-24,999) High range (\\$100,000+). I selected rows that did not have any ProsperRating_Combined value to explore. I plotted a lineplot with the rows for BorrowerAPR against IncomeRange to see how the borrowers without ratings from Prosper loan fared in terms of their BorrowerAPR. I was surprised to see that their borrower annual percentage rate (borrowerAPR) was even lower than those with ratings which led me to believe that IncomeRange was equally as important as the prosper rating.

IncomeRange featured also helped me uncover the reason as to why more loans were taken in year 2013 and why the number of loans dropped in year 2014. This was noticed when I plotted the BorrowerAPR across Year and IncomeRange as it showed the influx of Not_employed and Not_displayed IncomeRange in 2013 which increased their borrowerAPR and influenced the number of loans gotten that year. The following year 2014 showed fewer IncomeRange borrowers only from Very_low to High. I also examined the relationship of other features and realized that though the DebtToIncomeRatio did not have any correlation with my main feature of interest (BorrowerAPR), it showed a weak negative correlation to ProsperRating_Combined.
